{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "In the Arunta and Ilpirra tribes when a boy's nose has been bored, that is as soon as the operation has been completed, he strips a piece of bark off a gum tree, if possible, and throws it as far as he can in the direction of the Alcheringa camp of his mother, that is where the spirit individual of which his mother is the reincarnation lived in the Alcheringa.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca14:spirit-individual:001", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Totemic Ceremonies", "evidence_sha256": "f6f0c1abbe54555343bc2347f3867cd17316a98f72369b6c0aeaa1de4dfac3c1", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca14", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "spirit individual", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "spirit individual in Totemic Ceremonies", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "There is very clear evidence that during a former stage cannibalism was a well-recognised custom. We have already described certain ceremonies performed at the Engwura which can only be regarded as pointing back to the existence of a different state of affairs from that which now obtains. For example, in the Quabarra Ingwurninga inkinja, 1 two men had their bodies decorated with circles of white down which were supposed to represent the skulls of slain and eaten men. The performers themselves represented the Ulthana or spirits of the dead men wandering about in search of those who had killed and eaten them. In another ceremony two.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca14:ulthana:002", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Totemic Ceremonies", "evidence_sha256": "4a39b2a30afe6eaca9813820a537aaee6e3c909daac87ffef3657dfe88aec80c", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca14", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Ulthana", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Ulthana in Totemic Ceremonies", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "not_accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "rejected", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Next: Chapter XIII. The Customs of Kurdaitcha and Illapurinja and the Avenging Party or Atninga", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca14:kurdaitcha:003", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "insufficient_person_form_evidence", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "reviewed_context", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Totemic Ceremonies", "evidence_sha256": "450016d25a6931ab01caecf09759f18c0a010cc8b5076ac4a010382598b61fef", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca14", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "rejected", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "context_only", "source_label": "Kurdaitcha", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Kurdaitcha in Totemic Ceremonies", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca14.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "No idea of natural death—Death of one individual must be avenged in the normal condition of the tribe by the death of another—Organisation of a Kurdaitcha party—The ceremony of dislocating a toe before a man becomes entitled to wear the so-called Kurdaitcha shoes—The Kurdaitcha man accompanied by a Medicine man—Decoration of the two men—Killing the victim and operations of the Medicine man—Another form in which the Kurdaitcha man goes alone—The shoes do not serve to hide the tracks, and can only prevent who made them from being known—The Illapurinja—A form of female Kurdaitcha—The decoration of the woman—How the enemy is.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:kurdaitcha:004", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "ed21c55582c603c7d40bc07ae176fb56f5e0b1f78f080649196b2462bda1aba1", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Kurdaitcha", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Kurdaitcha in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "AMONGST the Central Australian natives there is no such thing as belief in natural death; however old or decrepit a man or woman may be when this takes place it is at once supposed that it has been brought about by the magic influence of some enemy, and in the normal condition of the tribe the death of one individual is followed by the murder of some one else who is supposed to be guilty of having caused the death. Not infrequently the dying man will whisper in the ear of a Railtchawa, or medicine man, the name of the man whose magic is killing him. If this be not done then there is no difficulty, by some other method, of fixing.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:medicine-man:005", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "0cb05a6d0de530e70a5325b20f6ea2d0862e3a777a90c8568d5e270d02188e04", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Medicine man", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Medicine man in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "When it is known who the culprit is a Kurdaitcha party may be arranged to avenge the death. This custom is, so the natives say, much less frequently carried out at the present day than in former years, and in the southern parts of the tribe seems to have died out altogether. 1 When it is decided who is guilty, a council of the old men of the group to which the dead man belonged is held and, if it be decided that vengeance is to be exacted by means of a Kurdaitcha party, then the man who is to play this part is chosen. The name Kurdaitcha is applied to the latter 2 and he wears the shoes to which by white men the name of Kurdaitcha.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:kurdaitcha:006", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "b8ed3c521d228674e0f43d90710fe3f79f535fdc73291925d183532b4de03046", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Kurdaitcha", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Kurdaitcha in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Before a man may wear the shoes he has to submit to a most painful ordeal. A stone is heated to redness and then applied to the ball of the small toe of either foot, it does not matter which, until, as the natives say, the joint is softened when with a sudden jerk, the toe is pulled outwards and the joint is thus dislocated. There is no doubt that some such ordeal as this is passed through, as we have examined feet of men who claim to be what is called Ertwa Kurdaitcha at Charlotte Waters, Crown Point on the Finke River, Owen Springs and Alice Springs amongst the Macdonnell Ranges, all of which show the remarkable peculiarity of.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:kurdaitcha:007", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "4549105dea179c8b6ff56c32ebbe4271ad0ba8e1684bd70556c87698691a1d0a", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Kurdaitcha", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Kurdaitcha in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Each Kurdaitcha man when going on his errand is accompanied by a medicine man and the two men are rubbed over with charcoal—black being in the Arunta tribe the colour associated with magic—and decorated with bands of white down. The hair of both men is tied up behind and a small conical helmet of twigs is fastened on with hair string. The Kurdaitcha himself has lines of down passing across the front of the helmet, down the side of the face and front of the body and legs as far as the knees. The medicine man has a median line running from the top of the helmet to the tip of his nose; another curved line meeting this at both ends.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:medicine-man:008", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "1fc4a998c7ced26efd7ba38ea12185cf9bb376d0772d00d243e1051962022a94", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Medicine man", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Medicine man in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "the eye of each side; and on the body a broad band of charcoal runs across from shoulder to shoulder and downwards till, at the level of the sternum, it divides into two, one passing on either side of the mid line and so on as far down as the knee. The bands are outlined with white down, and, as the pattern is a constant one, the Kurdaitcha man can always be distinguished from the medicine man.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:medicine-man:009", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "8fd5d869148681fb8038e4f33f2602a6f178f00bf6b70a46207d9dfe9c8e139a", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Medicine man", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Medicine man in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Then the medicine man falls into the rear while the Kurdaitcha stealthily creeps forward towards his quarry and suddenly rising up, spears him before he is aware of the presence of an enemy.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:medicine-man:010", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "descriptive_belief_record", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "b0fb2c8d007498807844be95610910db91d8cb1cc90a869c0fbd7c46af9ba814", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Medicine man", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Medicine man in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Most probably the explanation is, not that the native cannot follow the track, but that either he persuades himself that he cannot, or, what is still more likely, that the fear of the magic power of the dreaded Kurdaitcha causes him, if he catches sight of such a track, to avoid as much as possible the spot where he has seen it, in just the same way in which an ordinary European peasant will avoid the spot haunted by a ghost.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:ghost:011", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "apparition_account", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "0cf58c0d406e0282f9bfd6b032bbe9e892cb42a04ce2f97351910abf080e40e8", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "ghost", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "ghost in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "This is the only case which has come to our knowledge in which a woman is decorated with down fixed on with blood, and in which she actually handles a Churinga. The latter, of course, is not one of the ancestral Churinga, but it is regarded as being a sacred stick, and is spoken of as a Churinga just as are certain other similarly shaped sticks which are used in various ceremonies, for which they may be specially made. All that the woman is told is that the stick has been sung over, and is what is called Arungquiltha, that is, charged with magic and evil influence.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:arungquiltha:012", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "8571ca4a72e2d88fefcde7067d9612afeed7678cb4d738225b5ba95d157875c0", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Arungquiltha", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Arungquiltha in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "Travelling back to the Arunta country, the Atninga party separated into various contingents, each of which went to its own locality, upon arrival at which certain ceremonies had to be observed. The Alice Springs contingent, which will serve to illustrate what took place in each instance, halted some distance away from the main camp and decorated their bodies, painting them all over with powdered charcoal and placing on their foreheads and through the septum of the nose small twigs of a species of Eremophila. As soon as they came in sight of the main camp they began to perform an excited war-dance, approaching in the form of a.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:ulthana:013", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "db3ba6922b54e503258666e49b03b576444cc01f8b96b4e9de4190033e3f4b9d", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Ulthana", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Ulthana in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "It is supposed to be very effective as a means of frightening the Ulthana, that is the spirit of the dead man.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:ulthana:014", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "fb70f47bbd1c004bf6f8d316cde047519a8c0bec138307dfc9879547c3d251f5", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Ulthana", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Ulthana in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "The Ulthana or spirit of the dead man is supposed to follow the party in the form of a little bird called Chichurkna and is constantly on the look-out to injure the Immirinja.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca15:ulthana:015", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Magic", "evidence_sha256": "155738ee2f19e5de8d06fa2f56d7bd9343f4b43d83cee6469224f8caed901aae", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca15", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Ulthana", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Ulthana in Magic", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca15.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca16.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "It is generally supposed that amongst Australian natives the name of a dead man is never mentioned. This is not however strictly true as regards the Arunta tribe. There are various degrees of silence to be observed by different persons and these are dependent upon the mutual relationship which existed between the dead and living individual. During the period of mourning which follows immediately upon the death of a man and occupies a period of from twelve to eighteen months, no person must mention the name of the deceased except it be absolutely necessary to do so, and then only in a whisper for fear of disturbing and annoying the.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca16:ghost:016", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "apparition_account", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Burial and Mourning", "evidence_sha256": "ff2e484ecf119967154358206306d6631bd67673ce30f63e9bf0cf90a79b74b2", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca16", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "ghost", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "ghost in Burial and Mourning", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca16.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca21.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "In these ceremonies also only a limited number ever take part as actual performers, and, instead of occupying a long time in their performance, they usually last only a few minutes. Unlike those of the ordinary dances, also, the design always has a definite significance, and is supposed in many cases to have been handed down from the Alcheringa, while in others the decorations have been shown to the owner of the quabara by the Iruntarinia, or spirits. These ceremonies, again, are never passed on from tribe to tribe, but are in the possession of certain individuals who have received them by right of inheritance, that is, they may.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca21:iruntarinia:017", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Sacred Objects and Ceremonies", "evidence_sha256": "40c8adfcb6e2f735bad4032cef3073c0acf81979847f010f13ada7035554e428", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca21", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "Iruntarinia", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "Iruntarinia in Sacred Objects and Ceremonies", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca21.htm"}
{"acceptance_decision": "accepted", "access_date": "2026-06-22", "australian_relation": "Central Australian public-domain ethnographic text.", "candidate_status": "accepted", "canonical_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca21.htm", "coordinate_evidence_note": "", "cultural_sensitivity": "moderate", "duplicate_check_status": "source_url_external_id_and_excerpt_hash_checked", "ethics_review_status": "public_context_reviewed", "evidence_summary": "The exact significance of this can only be a matter of conjecture, p. 630 for the natives have not, so far as we can find out, any idea with regard to its origin or meaning. The decoration evidently points to the fact that it has some relation to a human being, and possibly we may have in the Kauaua the expression of the idea of the association of a spirit individual with a tree. We find, it must be remembered, amongst the Arunta tribe that trees are intimately associated with particular celebrated individuals of the Alcheringa whose spirits especially frequent those which are their Nanja trees, and, whilst there is no such thing.", "external_id": "sprint-ista-central-australi:ntca21:spirit-individual:018", "geocode_source": "", "geocode_verification_status": "", "humanoid_basis": "explicit_supernatural_or_anomalous_person_form_agent", "latitude": "", "location_precision": "region", "location_role": "cultural_association_region", "location_text": "Central Australia, NT", "longitude": "", "narrative_type": "spirit_person_narrative", "publication_date_text": "1899", "publication_or_organisation": "Native Tribes of Central Australia; Baldwin Spencer and F. J. Gillen", "publicness_status": "public_domain_public_web", "quality_class": "B", "raw_metadata_json": {"chapter": "Sacred Objects and Ceremonies", "evidence_sha256": "c8ff6c2ff3f16db70a93cd1fbd536f836754bda91342af3fa99e48137c302c58", "route_id": "sprint_ista_central_australia_exact_texts", "scope_classifier": "term_and_person_form_gate_v1", "section_id": "ntca21", "source_family": "structured_public_domain_books"}, "rejection_reason": "", "rights_access_status": "public_access_text_available", "secondary_role": "source_grounded_section_record", "source_label": "spirit individual", "source_name": "Internet Sacred Text Archive", "source_tier": "A", "source_type": "public_domain_transcribed_book", "title": "spirit individual in Sacred Objects and Ceremonies", "url": "https://sacred-texts.com/aus/ntca/ntca21.htm"}
